<br>
For example a relational database system 'software' means the executable code and processes by which the software creates the end product/result. This does not include the actual data or structures associated with it. <br>
<br>
The data the OPT files, created and stored locally, belong to you, not to Verant. (they would have a hard time proving I gave them license to use my PC to store  their data rent free)<br>
<br>
The data stored on Verant's servers i.e. account information and inventory data belongs to Verant. Dont mess with that EVER. Also dont mess with compiled code, graphics, and other binary data that ships directly from Verant. All of that is copyrighted material.<br>
<br>
Another point is what language is EQ written in? I would bet its a third party tool, not a proprietary language. If so then creating and modifying files on your PC thru the use of a prepackaged software product and the windows API most likely. <br>
<br>
By anology this would be like Microsoft saying they OWN all of your Word Documents. You cant reverse engineer Word legally, but you can sure use any third party tool you choose to look at and modify any document YOU create. (Microsoft covers their bases here by not allowing you to use their languages to compete in any market segment with one of their products so you cant develop a word reader from scratch with a microsoft language)<br>
<br>
Another and even closer analogy would be a browser cookie. Who owns the cookies on your PC? What are you allowed to do with these cookies? You own the cookie even though the web site application created it via the windows API, no questions asked. Secondly anything you want, its your cookie.<br>
<br>
Microsoft has very specific guidelines on what and what you cant OWN using thier software enviroments as a development platform, and if it uses Windows in any way (i.e. windows API) then Verant has to play by Microsoft's rules. Wheels within wheels, Verant has a mehtod of encoding data to be stored on your hard drive, but does so at a very high level. There are several layers that the data goes thru, using tools of others, to finally get to the low level data storage on your hard drive. All of which would require Verant to hold exclusive license to these layes as they relate to the files in particular.<br>
<br>
My best guess is that using C++ of some variety and utilizing standard windows (microsoft) API calls is how the files in question are actually written out to your PC. <br>
<br>
Every software application that creates data files uses a proprietary data structure (even if it is someone elses such as Microsoft's windows ini structure). <br>
<br>
Now, are you allowed to read this data and modify it? Yes on both counts using the tools within Everquest, at a MINIMUM. So if you are allowed to read the data, and you are allowed to modify it.. I dont see a great leap that you could open notepad or hexedit and modify your data directly. I have on numerous occasions because I cant stand manually retyping macros from one character to another. There are a variety of 3rd party tools available now that can do this. <br>
<br>
If the file structure were available in the public domain, which it is as referenced in the above post regarding a c header, then that information could be used to create a tool that would accomplish the objective without reverse engineering the files. <br>
<br>
The real question here is what harm would it cause Verant to allow 3rd party tools to modify these files, that would be what damages would be based upon. You may remeber the people who printed tshirts with the code to decrypt DVDs some time back. End result is the DVD format is wide open now.<br>
<br>
Finally contract law is pretty basic on this point, if it isnt specifically prohibited, then its allowed. On the other hand, if a legal rep from Verant, and not just a developer, sent you a letter or email saying cease and desist, then by all means do so unless you want to litigate. Personally, I think it would be worth it and I would dontate to the cause. Call your local bar association and for a minimnal fee (usually around $40) they will provide you with a lawyer who is a specialist in this type of law for a consultaion call. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#003366><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub92.ezboard.com/uglimwinnettlefoot.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Glimwin Nettlefoot</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Author</span><br>  Posts: 32<br> <font color=#FFFF33>(1/14/02 9:07:08 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub92.ezboard.com/feqannouncefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Software Engineering</span><hr size=1> I've already brought it up with him, and although it makes perfect sense to me -- I'm not going to jeopardize the &quot;Authority&quot; I have been given to release this as it is.<br>
